\label{lem:polytope}
The set $\Delta^W_{a}$ is a compact and convex set for any $a\in A$ .
Moreover , the set of extreme points of $\Delta^W_{a}$ , denoted $\mathrm{ext}(\Delta_a^W)$ , is finite for any $a\in A$ .
\end{lemma}  \begin{proof}
Fix
$a\in A$ .
The set
\begin{equation*}
C=\bigcap_{a'\in A}\left\{\mu\in\mathbb{R}^{|\Omega|}:\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)\left[\exp(\theta u(a',\omega))-\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))\right]\leq 0\right\}.
\end{equation*}
is a closed convex polyhedron , i.e. , the intersection of a finite number of closed half - spaces .
As $\Delta^W_a=C\cap\Delta(\Omega)$ and $\Delta(\Omega)$ is bounded , it is therefore a closed convex polytope ( i.e. , a bounded closed convex polyhedron ) .
Hence , it is a compact and convex set for every $a\in A$ .
Finally , since a convex polytope has a finite number of extreme points
\citep[][Corollary 8.4.2]{Panik1993} it has to be that $\Delta^W_a$ has a finite number of extreme points .
