Next lemma then identifies a finite set of Bayesian posterior beliefs over which Sender 's optimal information policy might be supported on .
\begin{lemma}  \label{lem:lipnowski_mathevet}
There exists an optimal information policy $p\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)$ such that $\mathrm{supp}(p)$ contains at most $|\Omega|$ affinely independent beliefs in the set $\mathcal{E}^W=\bigcup_{a\in A}\mathrm{ext}(\Delta^W_{a})$ .
\end{lemma}  \begin{proof}
The proof follows from \citet*{Lipnowski2017}
Theorem 1 .
\end{proof}  \cref{lem:lipnowski_mathevet} states that Sender 's optimal policy must be supported on at most $|\Omega|$ posteriors which are extreme points of some $(\Delta^W_{a})_{a\in A}$ .
As any of the sets $\Delta^W_{a}$ are polytopes , i.e. , sets defined by a finite number of closed affine inequalities , their extreme points are simply given by points in the probability simplex where a sufficient number of such affine inequalities bind .
More precisely , for any $a\in A$ , a posterior $\mu$ belongs to $\mathrm{ext}(\Delta_a^W)$ if and only if $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and exactly $|\Omega|-1$ of the constraints
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)\left[\exp(\theta u(a',\omega))-\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))\right]\leq0 \quad \text{for all} \quad a'\neq a
\end{equation*}
are binding .
In intuitive terms , extreme points of any $\Delta^W_{a}$ thus correspond either to beliefs at which Receiver is perfectly certain of the state or to extreme beliefs at which a wishful Receiver would be indifferent between at least two actions .
Thus , to find an optimal information policy , one just has to find the best of a finite number of convex combinations of such beliefs which satisfy Bayes - plausibility .
This is done by solving the following finite linear program
