\subsubsection{Proof for \cref{prop:opt_belief_2x2} } \label{secap:optim_belief_2x2}
The optimal belief of Receiver is solution to the problem
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optim_porblem_2x2}
\max_{\eta\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]}W(\eta,\mu)
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation*}
W(\eta,\mu)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\eta u_{0}^{1}+(1-\eta)u_{0}^{0}-\frac{1}{\theta}\left[\eta\ln\left(\frac{\eta}{\mu}\right)+(1-\eta)\ln\left(\frac{1-\eta}{1-\mu}\right)\right] & \text{if} \quad \eta<\lambda \\
\eta u_{1}^{1}+(1-\eta)u_{1}^{0}-\frac{1}{\theta}\left[\eta\ln\left(\frac{\eta}{\mu}\right)+(1-\eta)\ln\left(\frac{1-\eta}{1-\mu}\right)\right]  & \text{if} \quad \eta\geq\lambda
\end{array}
\right.,
\end{equation*}
for any $\eta,\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
This function is continuous , as $\lambda$ is such that $\lambda u_{0}^{1}+(1-\lambda)u_{0}^{0}=\lambda u_{1}^{1}+(1-\lambda)u_{1}^{0}$ , over the compact set $\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ so a solution to problem \labelcref{eqn:optim_porblem_2x2} exists .
Moreover , $W$ is twice continuously differentiable and strictly concave on the sets $[0,\lambda[$ and $[\lambda,1]$ so any critical point lying in $[0,\lambda[$ ( resp. $[\lambda,1]$ ) is a global maximum on $[0,\lambda[$ ( resp. $[\lambda,1]$ ) .
The first order condition associated with action $0$ is
\begin{equation*}
-\delta_0-\frac{1}{\theta}\left[\ln\left(\frac{\eta}{\mu}\right)-\ln\left(\frac{1-\eta}{1-\mu}\right)\right]=0
\end{equation*}
whereas the first order condition associated with action $1$ is
\begin{equation*}
\delta_1-\frac{1}{\theta}\left[\ln\left(\frac{\eta}{\mu}\right)-\ln\left(\frac{1-\eta}{1-\mu}\right)\right]=0
\end{equation*}
Solving both equations for $\eta$ yields
\begin{equation*}
\eta_{0}(\mu)=\frac{\mu}{\mu+(1-\mu)\exp(\theta \delta_0)},
\end{equation*}
and
\begin{equation*}
\eta_{1}(\mu)=\frac{\mu\exp(\theta \delta_1)}{\mu\exp(\theta \delta_1)+(1-\mu)},
\end{equation*}
for any $\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
Now , which belief is going to be adopted depends on the value of the well - being under that belief .
In this setting we have
\begin{equation*}
W_a(\mu)=\eta_a(\mu) u_{a}^{1}+(1-\eta_a(\mu))u_{a}^{0}-\frac{1}{\theta}\left[\eta_a(\mu)\ln\left(\frac{\eta_a(\mu)}{\mu}\right)+(1-\eta_a(\mu))\ln\left(\frac{1-\eta_a(\mu)}{1-\mu}\right)\right]
\end{equation*}
for any $a\in\{0,1\}$ , which simplifies to
\begin{equation*}
W_a(\mu)=\frac{1}{\theta}\ln\left(\mu\exp(\theta u_a^1)+(1-\mu)\exp(\theta u_a^0)\right),
\end{equation*}
for any $a\in\{0,1\}$ .
Therefore , the Bayesian posterior at which Receiver is indifferent ( in terms of well - being ) between choosing belief $\eta_{0}(\mu)$ and $\eta_{1}(\mu)$ is solution ( if it exists ) to the equation $W_0(\mu)=W_1(\mu)$ which reduces to
\begin{equation*}
\mu\exp(\theta u_0^1)+(1-\mu)\exp(\theta u_0^0)=\mu\exp(\theta u_1^1)+(1-\mu)\exp(\theta u_1^0),
\end{equation*}
and admits
\begin{equation*}
\tilde{\mu}=\frac{\exp(\theta u_0^0)-\exp(\theta u_1^0)}{\exp(\theta u_0^0)-\exp(\theta u_1^0)+\exp(\theta u_1^1)-\exp(\theta u_0^1)},
\end{equation*}
as a unique solution .
Therefore , belief $\eta_{0}(\mu)$ is chosen by Receiver whenever $\mu\leq\tilde{\mu}$ and belief $\eta_{1}(\mu)$ is chosen whenever $\mu\geq\tilde{\mu}$ .
Note that without any tie - breaking rule , Receiver 's belief correspondence at the indifference belief would be $\eta(\tilde{\mu})=\{\eta_0(\tilde{\mu}),\eta_1(\tilde{\mu})\}$ .
Hence , it remains to prove that $\eta(\tilde{\mu})=\eta_1(\tilde{\mu})$ .

