It is clear from \cref{fig:optim_belief_distortion} that Receiver distorts her belief in the direction of events associated with higher utility ( namely state $\omega=0$ when taking action $a=0$ and $\omega=1$ when taking action $a=1$ ) .
Furthermore , the intensity of the belief distortion is closely tied to the intensity of preferences , i.e. , the degree of asymmetry of the payoff matrix .
Formally , the likelihood ratio $\eta_a(\mu)/\mu$ is increasing in $\delta_a$ if $a=1$ and decreasing if $a=0$ .
In other terms , Receiver 's optimism about state $\omega=1$ increases with the excess utility of action $a=1$ whereas it is decreasing with the excess utility of action $a=0$ .
In \cref{fig:optim_belief_distortion} , the belief distortion gives a prominent place to the state of the world $\omega=1$ because it is associated with the highest attainable payoff .
Finally , the concavity ( resp. convexity ) of the distortion can be explained as follows : at very precise posterior beliefs , i.e. , close to $\mu=0$ or $\mu=1$ , the marginal cost of belief distortion becomes very high for Receiver .
Conversely , ambiguous beliefs , i.e. , close to $\mu=1/2$ are easier to distort .
In intuitive terms , experiments of Sender generating imprecise beliefs give more room to self - deception for a wishful thinker , whereas it is very difficult for a wishful thinker to self - deceive when facing a very informative experiment .
This characteristic is consistent with findings in psychology showing that self - deception requires the decision maker 's informational environment to be `` vague ' ' \citep*{Sloman2010} .

Finally , under some Bayesian posterior $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and for some $a\in A$ , Receiver has to hold belief defined in \cref{eqn:belief_distortion_infinite} if and only if $W_a(\mu)\geq W_{a'}(\mu)$ for all $a'\neq a$ , that is
\begin{equation}\label{eq:expected_distorted_utility}
\int_{\Omega}\exp(\theta u(a,\cdot)) \, \mathrm{d}\mu\geq\int_{\Omega}\exp(\theta u(a',\cdot))\, \mathrm{d}\mu,
\end{equation}
for all $a'\neq a$ .
By definition $\eta_a(\mu)$ must belong to $\Delta_a^B$ implying $a(\eta_a(\mu))=a$ for any $a\in A$ .
Moreover , the optimal belief is $\eta_a(\mu)$ whenever the distorted expected utility in \cref{eq:expected_distorted_utility} is maximized with respect to $a$ .
Hence , the wishful thinker behaves as if his expected utility with respect to the induced posterior of Sender was given by \cref{eq:expected_distorted_utility} .
This proves \cref{prop:opt_behavior_KL} .
