\begin{equation*}
\Delta_a^W=\{\mu\in\Delta(\Omega): a\in A(\eta(\mu))\}
\end{equation*}
for any $a\in A$ .
The set $\Delta_a^B$ ( resp. $\Delta_a^W$ ) corresponds to the \emph{set of Bayesian posteriors supporting action            as an optimal action for a Bayesian (resp. wishful Receiver)} .
We show in \cref{secap:general_comp_stat} that those set are of primary importance to make comparisons between Sender 's policies and welfare since it turns out that ( i ) in either KG 's or our framework , Sender 's optimal policies are respectively supported on extreme points of those sets and ( ii ) comparing those sets tells us what action a wishful Receiver takes under a larger set of beliefs compared to a Bayesian .
Accordingly , we say that an action $a\in A$ is \textit{privileged} by a wishful Receiver if and only if $\Delta_a^B \subseteq \Delta_a^W$ .

It is interesting to remark a couple of things concerning the optimal belief of Receiver .
First , the wishful thinker holds a distorted subjective belief with respect to the Bayesian benchmark if and only if the resulting action $a\in A$ does not lead to a sure payoff , such that \textit{only preferences constitute a motive for Receiver to distort her beliefs} .
\footnote{This fact has already been highlighted by \citet*{Caplin2019} and is consistent with finding of \citet*{Exley2019} .
Namely , they show experimentally that when one removes any self - serving incentive to distort beliefs , participants actually appear unbiased .
We show in \cref{secap:extensions_as1} that this result extends to the case of cost functions meeting \cref{as:1} . }
\begin{corollary}
[ Stakes - dependent beliefs ]
\label{cor:stakes-dependent_beliefs_KL}
For any posterior $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ we have $\eta(\mu)\neq\mu$ if , and only if $u(a,\omega)\neq u(a,\omega')$ for some $\omega\neq\omega'$ .
