\end{equation*}
by \cref{prop:opt_behavior_KL} .
We can see from \cref{eqn:opt_belief_voteri} that , due to the heterogeneity in $\beta$ , there is always some level of belief polarization among wishful voters for any $\mu\in\mathopen]0,1\mathclose[$ .
Let us define as a measure of such polarization the sum of the absolute difference between each pair of beliefs in the audience :
\begin{equation} \label{eqn:polarization}
\Pi(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\sum_{j=i+1}^{n} \eta_i(\mu) - \eta_j(\mu)
\end{equation}
for any $\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
\footnote{Note that we can always index the voters in an ascending order of            , such that            for all            whenever            , such that \cref{eqn:polarization} does indeed represent the absolute difference between each pair of beliefs . }
\begin{proposition}  \label{prop:polarization}
Under Sender 's optimal strategy $p^*\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)$ , the signal that leads to the implementation of the proposal also generates the maximum polarization among voters .
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
See \cref{secap:polarization} .
\end{proof}
To build an intuition of why this is the case , let 's first first note that , in our model , belief polarization and action polarization are closely related .
Agents voting for the implementation of the proposal will distort their beliefs upwards , whereas agents voting for the status quo will distort their beliefs downwards .
We can thus see that maximum belief polarization should be attained for some belief for which action polarization is maximized , that is , for some belief at which $\frac{n+1}{2}$ agents are voting one way and the remaining $\frac{n-1}{2}$ are voting another way .
This will be the case for any $\mu \in [\tilde{\mu}_{m-1}, \tilde{\mu}_{m+1}[$ .
Indeed , whatever is the distribution of preferences , belief polarization will be maximized at some $\mu$ belonging to this interval .

As we show in \cref{par:illustration_beliefs_behavior_2x2} we have $\Delta_0^B=\mathopen[0,\lambda\mathclose]$ , $\Delta_1^B=\mathopen[\lambda,1\mathclose]$ , $\Delta_0^W=\mathopen[0,\tilde{\mu}\mathclose]$ and $\Delta_1^W=\mathopen[\tilde{\mu},1\mathclose]$ , so action $a=0$ is privileged whenever $\tilde{\mu}>\lambda$ whereas action $a=1$ is privileged when $\tilde{\mu}<\lambda$ .
Next proposition precisely states when a wishful Receiver privileges action $a=1$ .
\begin{proposition}  \label{prop:comp_stat_2x2}
Action $a=1$ is privileged by a wishful Receiver if , and only if : \begin{enumerate} [ ( i ) ] \ item $\delta_{\max}\leq 0$ and $\delta_0<\delta_1$ , or ; \ item $\delta_{\max}<0$ , $\delta_0>\delta_1$ and $\theta>\theta_\lambda$ , or ; \ item $\delta_{\max}>0$ , $\delta_0<\delta_1$ and $\theta<\theta_\lambda$ .
\end{enumerate} where $\theta_\lambda$ is a strictly positive threshold such that
\begin{equation*}
\tilde{\mu}(\theta_\lambda)=\lambda.
\end{equation*}
\end{proposition}  \begin{proof}
See \cref{secap:compstat_2x2}  \end{proof}

The health agency wants to maximize the probability of individuals adopting the preventive treatment so its payoff is given by $v(a,\omega)=a$ for all $(a,\omega)\in\{0,1\}\times\{\munderbar{\sigma},\bar{\sigma}\}$ .
\footnote{Maximizing the probability of adoption is actually a sensible objective. Most infections cause negative externalities due to their transmission through social interactions. Therefore, a benevolent planner who wants to reduce the likelihood of transmission of an infection would do well to maximize the rate of adoption of the preventive treatment (for example, maximize condom distribution to control AIDS transmission, maximize injection of vaccines to control viral infections, or maximize mask use to control the spread of airborne diseases).}
The agency informs individuals about the prevalence of the disease by designing and committing to an information policy $p\in\Delta(\mathopen[0,1\mathclose])$ such that
\begin{equation*}
\int_{0}^{1}\mu\,\mathrm{d}p(\mu)=\mu_0.
\end{equation*}
Remark first that a Bayesian Receiver would adopt the following behavior
\begin{equation*}
a(\mu)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu\geq\lambda \\
0 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu<\lambda
\end{array}\right.,
\end{equation*}
where
\begin{equation*}
\lambda=\frac{c-\alpha\munderbar{\sigma}s}{\alpha(\bar{\sigma}-\munderbar{\sigma})s},
\end{equation*}
for any posterior belief
$\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
