As a result of \cref{cor:sender_comp_stat_2x2} , Sender always needs to induce higher beliefs for Receiver to adopt the treatment than he would need if he faced a Bayesian agent , all the more so when Receiver 's ability to self - deceive $\theta$ becomes larger .
Therefore in this example , overoptimism of Receiver \emph{always complicates} Sender 's persuasion task .
The reason for this can again be interpreted easily : \emph{Receiver's optimism bias and Sender's interests are always misaligned} .

In our model , however , Receiver is not a Bayesian statistician but a wishful thinker .
She distorts her beliefs towards more desirable states .
We model this belief formation process as an actual optimization problem over the set of beliefs .
This modelling assumption means that Receiver processes information \textit{as if she were distorting optimally the Bayesian posterior induced by Sender's experiment} .
Following CL , we assume the belief of Receiver optimally trades - off her anticipated payoff against the cost of holding distorted beliefs .
\footnote{In their model, however, the decision maker distorts his beliefs in a self-serving manner in order to confirm his choice ex-post. In contrast, we assume that Receiver's belief formation takes place after information disclosure but before Receiver's decision. As a result, she distorts Sender's induced Bayesian posterior \emph{while taking into account how such beliefs will impact her future decision} .}
Let us define Receiver 's psychological well - being function as
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:wellbeing}
W(\eta,\mu)= \mathbb{E}_{\eta}u(a(\eta),\omega)-\frac{1}{\theta}\, C(\eta,\mu)
\end{equation}
where $\theta$ is a strictly positive weight parameter describing Receiver 's ability to self - deceive and $C:\Delta(\Omega)\times\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}_{+}$ is the cost function from distorting the Bayesian posterior belief $\mu$ induced by Sender 's experiment .
We make the following assumptions about the cost function :
\begin{assumption} [ Belief distortion cost ]
\label{as:1}
The function $C:\Delta(\Omega)\times\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ is $\mathcal{C}^2$ and submodular for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and the function $C(\cdot,\mu):\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}_+$ is \begin{enumerate} [ ( i ) ]
\ item strictly convex ; \ item minimized at $\eta=\mu$ ; \item essentially smooth on the probability simplex.\footnote{Formally,            is essentially smooth if it is continuously differentiable over            and            for any            -valued sequence            such that            . See Chapter 26 of \citet*{Rockafellar1970} . }
\end{enumerate}
\end{assumption}
\cref{as:1} has been first introduced by \citet*{Bracha2012} who also model overoptimism as an endogenous choice of beliefs .
We defer the discussion of those assumption as well as the possible explanations for such a cost to \cref{sec:discussion} .
In what follows , the cost function is generally represented by measures of dissimilarity between probability distributions , such as the Kullback - Leibler divergence plotted in \cref{fig:ex_cost_func} for a binary state space .
In particular , the Kullback - Leibler divergence satisfies \cref{as:1} .
Our main results will be presented for this specification of the cost function .
We extend our analysis to the more general case of cost functions meeting \cref{as:1} as well as to alternative specifications in \cref{secap:extensions} .
