It turns out that the welfare comparison for Sender with respect to KG is simple .
If the prior is such that Receiver initially wants to take action 0 , Sender strictly benefits from facing a wishful Receiver whenever $\tilde{\mu}<\lambda$ as $\mathrm{cav}(\hat{v})(\mu_0)>\mathrm{cav}(v)(\mu_0)$ if and only if $\mu_0\in\mathopen[0,\lambda\mathclose]$ and $\tilde{\mu}<\lambda$ .
In case Sender benefits ( resp. does not ) from facing a wishful Receiver \emph{persuasion is also ``easier'' (resp. ``harder'') for Sender} in the following sense : Sender needs a strictly less ( resp. strictly more ) Blackwell informative information policy than KG to persuade Receiver to take his preferred action .
\footnote{When the state space is finite, a policy            such that all elements in            are affinely independent is (weakly) more Blackwell-informative than a policy            if and only if            , which, in the binary state space case reduces to            where            and            are such that            and            \citep[see][Lemma 2]{Lipnowski2020} .}
Equivalently , if experiments were costly to produce as in \citet*{Gentzkow2014} , then Sender would always need to consume less ( resp. more ) resources to persuade a wishful Receiver to take his preferred action than the Bayesian benchmark .
We show in \cref{sec:examples} that \cref{cor:sender_comp_stat_2x2} have economic consequences .

As Receiver and Sender 's beliefs will generally differ in our model , we denote $\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)$ the belief of Receiver and $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ the belief of Sender .
Receiver 's optimal action correspondence is denoted
\begin{equation*}
A(\eta)=\underset{a\in A}{\arg\max} \, \mathbb{E}_{\eta} u(a,\omega).
\end{equation*}
Without loss of generality , we assume that no action is trivially dominated , i.e. for any action $a\in A$ there always exists some belief $\eta$ such that $a\in A(\eta)$ .
When the set $A(\eta)$ has more than one element we break the tie in favor of Sender , as in KG .
That is , when Receiver holds belief $\eta$ , the action played in equilibrium is given by a selection $a(\eta)\in A(\eta)$ which maximizes Sender 's expected utility .
\footnote{There might be more than one such selection if there exists some            at which Sender is indifferent between some actions in            . In that case, we pick arbitrarily one of those actions.}

As Receiver 's belief optimally trades - off her anticipated utility and the distortion cost , her optimal choice of belief is the solution to the optimization problem
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optbeliefpb}
W(\mu)=\max_{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)} W(\eta,\mu),
\end{equation}
for any Bayesian belief $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Accordingly , Receiver 's optimal belief correspondence is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optbeliefpb_argmax}
\eta(\mu)=\underset{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)}{\arg\max}\; W(\eta,\mu),
\end{equation}
for any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Formally , given that the Bayesian belief is $\mu$ , the well - being of Receiver in the interim phase when she holds the optimal belief $\eta(\mu)$ is given by $W(\mu)$ .
We assume that , when Receiver is indifferent between several subjective posteriors at some Bayesian belief $\mu$ , i.e. , when $\eta(\mu)$ is set - valued at $\mu$ with at least two elements , she picks the one that maximizes Sender 's expected utility .
This tie breaking rule is innocuous and is only made for the sake of tractability : it ensures that the optimal belief correspondence $\eta:\Delta(\Omega)\rightrightarrows\Delta(\Omega)$ is actually a well defined function of $\mu$ and simplifies the characterization of the optimal information policy .

We make the assumption that , contrarily to Receiver , Sender updates his belief through Bayes rule and \emph{knows Sender's tendency to be a wishful thinker} .
Formally , Sender commits , at the ex-ante stage , to an information policy $p\in \mathcal{P}(\mu_0)$ where
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)=\left\{p\in\Delta(\Delta(\Omega)): \mathbb{E}_{p}\mu=\mu_0\right\}
\end{equation*}
is the set of Bayes - plausible distribution over posterior beliefs given the prior $\mu_0$ .
We know , since \citet*{Aumann1995} and KG , that it is equivalent to think in terms of information structure $\pi:\Omega\longrightarrow\Delta(S)$ or in terms of Bayes - plausible distributions over posteriors $p\in\Delta(\Delta(\Omega))$ .
\footnote{More precisely, Proposition 1 in KG shows that an information policy            is induced by some information structure            if and only if            and            . Formally, an information structure            induces            if (i)            ; (ii)             is given by Bayes rule \labelcref{eqn:bayes_rule} for any $\omega\in\Omega$ and $s\in S$ ; and ( iii ) the probability of a given posterior $\mu$ is given by
\begin{equation*}
p(\mu)=\sum_{\{s\in S: \mu(\cdot\mid s)=\mu\}}\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\pi(s\mid\omega)\mu_0(\omega),
\end{equation*}
for all $\mu\in\mathrm{supp}(p)$ .
Given an information policy $p\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)$ , it is always possible to determine the corresponding information structure by computing
\begin{equation*}
\pi(s\mid \omega)=\frac{\mu(\omega\mid s)p(\mu(\cdot\mid s))}{\mu_0(\omega)}
\end{equation*}
for all $s\in S$ and all $\omega\in\Omega$ . }

Let $\Omega$ be any Polish space and let $\Delta(\Omega)$ be the set of probability measures on $\Omega$ endowed with its Borel $\sigma$ - field , let also $\mathcal{B}(\Omega)$ be the set of bounded continuous and Borel - measurable real - valued functions on $\Omega$ .
In this general setting , the Kullback - Leibler divergence is given by
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu)=\int_\Omega \ln\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}\mu}{\mathrm{d}\eta}\right)\mathrm{d}\mu,
\end{equation*}
for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ , where $\frac{\mathrm{d}\mu}{\mathrm{d}\eta}$ is the Radon - Nikodym derivative of $\mu$ with respect to $\eta$ , defined whenever $\eta$ is absolutely continuous with respect to $\mu$ .
Remember , additionally , that the well - being function is defined by
\begin{equation*}
W(\eta,\mu)=\int_{\Omega} u(a,\cdot)\,\mathrm{d}\eta-\frac{1}{\theta}\int_\Omega \ln\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}\mu}{\mathrm{d}\eta}\right)\mathrm{d}\mu,
\end{equation*}
whenever $a(\eta)=a$ for some $a\in A$ , i.e. , whenever $\eta\in\Delta_a^B=\{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega):a(\eta)=a\}$ .
We can therefore identify Receiver 's optimal beliefs by : \begin{enumerate} [ ( i ) ]
\ item
Finding the maximum of $W(\eta,\mu)$ when fixing $a(\eta)=a$ .
This maximum corresponds to the optimal belief $\eta_a(\mu)$ Receiver would hold to justify action $a\in A$ as optimal under Sender 's induced posterior $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
\ item
Checking , for $a \in A$ , which $\eta_a(\mu)$ actually maximizes the function $W(\eta,\mu)$ overall .
As a corollary , solving the systems of inequalities $W_a(\mu)\geq W_{a'}(\mu)$ with $a'\neq a$ for any $a\in A$ identifies under which Bayesian posteriors Receiver would actually hold belief $\eta_a(\mu)$ .
\end{enumerate}
For any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ , by application of the Donsker - Varadhan variational formula \citep[see][Lemma 1.4.3]{Dupuis1997} we have
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:Donsker-Varadhan}
\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu)=\sup_{u(a,\cdot)\in\mathcal{B}(\Omega)}\left\{\int_{\Omega}\theta u(a,\cdot)\,\mathrm{d}\eta-\ln\left(\int_{\Omega}\exp(u(a,\cdot))\,\mathrm{d}\mu\right)\right\},
\end{equation}
for all $a\in A$ and $\theta\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{*}$ .
For any $u(a,\cdot)\in\mathcal{B}(\Omega)$ and $\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)$ , taking the Legendre - Fenchel 's dual to the variational equality \labelcref{eqn:Donsker-Varadhan} yields
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optimal_well_being_infinite}
\ln\left(\int_{\Omega}\exp(\theta u(a,\cdot))\,\mathrm{d}\mu\right)=\sup_{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)}\left\{\int_{\Omega}\theta u(a,\cdot)\,\mathrm{d}\eta-\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu)\right\},
\end{equation}
for any $a\in A$ and $\theta\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{*}$ \citep[see][Proposition 1.4.2]{Dupuis1997} .
Hence ,
\begin{equation*}
W_a(\mu)=\frac{1}{\theta}\ln\left(\int_{\Omega}\exp(\theta u(a,\cdot))\,\mathrm{d}\mu\right)
\end{equation*}
for any $a\in A$ , any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and any $\theta\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{*}$ .
Moreover , the supremum in \cref{eqn:optimal_well_being_infinite} is attained uniquely by the probability measure $\eta_a\in\Delta(\Omega)$ defined by
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:belief_distortion_infinite}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\eta_a}{\mathrm{d}\mu}=\frac{\exp(\theta u(a,\cdot))}{\int_{\Omega}\exp(\theta u(a,\cdot))\mathrm{d}\mu},
\end{equation}
for any $a\in A$ \citep[see, again,][Proposition 1.4.2]{Dupuis1997} .

Let us first define
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optim_belief_action_a}
\eta_a(\mu)=\underset{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)}{\arg\max}\; \mathbb{E}_{\eta}u(a,\omega)-\frac{1}{\theta}\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu),
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optim_wellbeing_action_a}
W_a(\mu)=\max_{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)}\mathbb{E}_{\eta}u(a,\omega)-\frac{1}{\theta}\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu),
\end{equation}
as the optimal belief and the optimal well - being Receiver would get if she would take action $a\in A$ and if Sender 's experiment would have induced the Bayesian posterior $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Accordingly , we call $\eta_a(\mu)$ Receiver 's optimal belief \emph{justifying action            under posterior            } and $W_a(\mu)$ Receiver 's optimal well - being when \emph{the optimal belief justifies action            under posterior            } .
\footnote{Those objects are precisely what CL are considering as, in their model, the decision maker chooses belief after his decision. Such that his belief choice justifies ex-post his previous decision.}
As we consider the belief choice is taking place after information disclosure but before Receiver 's decision , we have to take care of how the discontinuities in the equilibrium action function $a:\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow A$ affect the shape of the psychological well - being function .
Formally , the well - being function admits a kink at beliefs where Receiver is indifferent between two actions and is strictly concave on every part of the belief simplex where $a(\eta)=a$ for some $a\in A$ .
More precisely
\begin{equation*}
W(\eta,\mu)=\mathbb{E}_{\eta}u(a,\omega)-\frac{1}{\theta}\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu),
\end{equation*}
whenever $a(\eta)=a$ for some $a\in A$ .
\footnote{As already noted by \citet*{Bracha2012} as well as CL , the well - being function has a similar mathematical structure to the multiplier preferences developed in \citet*{Hansen2008} and axiomatized in \citet*{Maccheroni2006} and \citet*{Strzalecki2011} .
Precisely , the agent in \citet*{Strzalecki2011} chooses beliefs such as to solve
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:HansenSargent}
\min_{\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)}\mathbb{E}_{\eta}u(a,\omega)+\frac{1}{\theta}\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu),
\end{equation}
for every $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
In a persuasion setting the interpretation would be the following : the Receiver observes the realized posterior $\mu$ induced by Sender 's experiment , but does not have full confidence in it .
Rather , he considers that many other beliefs $\eta$ are plausible and that their degree of plausibility decreases in proportion to their dissimilarity to $\mu$ , as measured by the Kullback - Leibler divergence between $\eta$ and $\mu$ .
The parameter $\theta$ would thus measure the degree of confidence of Receiver in Sender 's belief $\mu$ or , in other words , the importance he attaches to belief misspecification .
Hence , conclusions on the belief distortion would naturally be reversed with respect to our model : a receiver forming beliefs according to \cref{eqn:HansenSargent} would form overcautious beliefs .
Studying how a rational Sender would persuade a Receiver concerned by robustness seems an interesting path for future research . }
We can therefore identify Receiver 's optimal beliefs by : \begin{enumerate}
[ ( i ) ]
\ item
Finding the maximum of $W(\eta,\mu)$ when fixing $a(\eta)=a$ .
This maximum corresponds to the optimal belief $\eta_a(\mu)$ Receiver would hold to justify action $a\in A$ under Sender 's induced posterior
$\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
\ item
Checking , for $a \in A$ , which $\eta_a(\mu)$ actually maximizes the function $W(\eta,\mu)$ overall .
As a corollary , solving the systems of inequalities $W_a(\mu)\geq W_{a'}(\mu)$ with $a'\neq a$ for any $a\in A$ identifies under which Bayesian posteriors Receiver would actually hold belief $\eta_a(\mu)$ .
\end{enumerate}
Next proposition characterizes the optimal beliefs of Receiver under any Bayesian posterior belief induced by Sender .
\footnote{This result is stated in the case where the state space is a finite set for the sake of consistency. We actually extend CL results to a more general setting. Namely, we assume            could be an Polish space and            could be any bounded, continuous and Borel-measurable function for any fixed            . We defer, however, the systematic study of our model with larger action and state spaces to future research.}  \begin{proposition} [ Receiver 's optimal beliefs ]
\label{prop:opt_belief_KL}
Assume $C(\eta,\mu)=\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu)$ for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Receiver 's optimal belief justifying action $a$ , defined in \cref{eqn:optim_belief_action_a} , equals
\begin{equation*}
\eta_a(\mu)=\left(\frac{\mu(\omega)\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))}{\sum_{\omega'\in\Omega}\mu(\omega')\exp(\theta u(a,\omega'))}\right)_{\omega\in\Omega}
\end{equation*}
while Receiver 's well - being when under belief $\eta_a$ , defined in \cref{eqn:optim_wellbeing_action_a} , equals
\begin{equation*}
W_a(\mu)=\frac{1}{\theta}\ln\left(\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))\right),
\end{equation*}
for any $a\in A$ and any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Hence , Receiver 's optimal belief equals
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:optim_belief_KL}
\eta(\mu)=\left(\frac{\mu(\omega)\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))}{\sum_{\omega'\in\Omega}\mu(\omega')\exp(\theta u(a,\omega'))}\right)_{\omega\in\Omega}
\end{equation}
whenever $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ is such that
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)\exp(\theta u(a,\omega))\geq\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\mu(\omega)\exp(\theta u(a',\omega)),
\end{equation*}
for all $a'\neq a$ .
\end{proposition}  \begin{proof}
See \cref{secap:optim_belief_KL} .
\end{proof}
The former proposition thus states that Receiver 's optimal belief correspondence is a discontinuous function of $\mu$ where discontinuities are located at Bayesian posterior beliefs such that Receiver is indifferent --- in terms of well - being --- between holding beliefs $\eta_a$ or $\eta_{a'}$ for some $a\neq a'$ .

Since Receiver 's belief choice characterizes how she would distort her belief away from any realized Bayesian posterior drawn from distribution $p\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)$ , Sender can thus choose the best information policy by backward induction , knowing ( i ) how Receiver will distort her posterior and ( ii ) how she will behave given the realized distorted posterior .
Sender 's information design problem hence writes
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:sender_optimization_pb}
\hat{V}(\mu_0)=\max_{p\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)}\ \mathbb{E}_{p}\hat{v}(\mu),
\end{equation}
where $\hat{v}$ is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:sender_exp_utility}
\hat{v}(\mu)= \mathbb{E}_{\mu}v(a(\eta(\mu)),\omega),
\end{equation}
for any Bayesian posterior $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
\ footnote
{ Also , in what follows , we denote by
\begin{equation}\label{KG_problem}
V(\mu_0)=\max_{p\in\mathcal{P}(\mu_0)}\ \mathbb{E}_{p}v(\mu),
\end{equation}
the optimal value Sender would obtain in KG 's environment , where
\begin{equation*}
v(\mu)=\mathbb{E}_{\mu}v(a(\mu),\omega),
\end{equation*}
for any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ . }
Remark that , in our environment , solving problem \labelcref{eqn:sender_optimization_pb} consists in solving the original problem of KG \labelcref{KG_problem} , i.e. , finding the information policy maximizing the expected utility of Sender under the Bayesian plausibility constraint , but where the indirect utility function of Sender takes the distorted belief of Receiver into account .
This has already been noted by \citet*{DeClippel2019} who extend the resolution method of KG to environments where Receiver updates her beliefs according to non-Bayesian updating rules which are systematic distortions with respect to the Bayesian posterior .
Formally , the \emph{concavification} of the distorted expected utility of Sender , i.e. , the smallest concave function everywhere above $\hat{v}$ , characterizes the value of the optimal information policy .
\begin{lemma}
[ Concavification works ]
\label{lem:concavification} When Receiver 's subjective posterior is given by the solution of \labelcref{eqn:optbeliefpb_argmax} and Sender 's indirect utility function is given by \labelcref{eqn:sender_exp_utility} , the value $\hat{V}(\mu_0)$ of any optimal information policy under the common prior $\mu_0$ equals $\mathrm{cav}(\hat{v})(\mu_0)$ where
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{cav}(\hat{v})(\mu)=\mathrm{sup}\left\{z\in\mathbb{R}: (\mu,z)\in\mathrm{co}(\hat{v})\right\}
\end{equation*}
for any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and $\mathrm{co}(\hat{v})$ denotes the closed convex hull of the graph of $\hat{v}$ .
\end{lemma}  \begin{proof}
The result follows from Corollary 2 in KG .
\end{proof}
Hence , importantly , the existence as well as the characterization of the solution to problem \labelcref{eqn:sender_optimization_pb} follow from KG .
Before turning to the main results , we discuss the main assumptions of the model .

Let us consider the example of a financial broker ( Sender ) designing reports about the profitability of some risky financial product to inform potential clients ( Receiver ) .
The profitability of the product is represented by $\omega\in\Omega=\{0,1\}$ , where $\omega = 0$ means that the the product yields low return and $\omega = 1$ that the product yields high returns .
Receiver has some saved up money she is willing to invest and chooses action $a\in A=\{0,1\}$ , where $a = 0$ represents the choice of non-investing in which case Receiver 's payoff is $0$ and $a = 1$ represents investing in the product of the broker , which yields a payoff of $1-\lambda$ when $\omega=1$ and $-\lambda$ when $\omega=0$ .
That is , Receiver 's material payoff is given by $u(a,\omega)=a(\omega-\lambda)$ , with $\lambda \in \mathopen]0,1\mathclose[$ for any $a,\omega\in\{0,1\}$ .
The broker is remunerated on the basis of a flat fee $v>0$ that is independent of the true product 's profitability , such that he wants the investor to take action $1$ regardless of the state .
Its material payoff is thus given by $v(a,\omega)=va$ .
The broker informs potential clients by designing and committing itself to an information policy $p\in\Delta(\mathopen[0,1\mathclose])$ such that
\begin{equation*}
\int_{0}^{1}\mu\,\mathrm{d}p(\mu)=\mu_0.
\end{equation*}
Remark first that a Bayesian Receiver would adopt the following behavior
\begin{equation*}
a(\mu)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu\geq\lambda \\
0 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu<\lambda
\end{array}\right.,
\end{equation*}
under any posterior belief $\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
In contrast , assume that Receiver is a wishful thinker and has a cost of belief distortion is given by $C(\eta,\mu)=\mathrm{D_{KL}}(\eta||\mu)$ for any $\eta,\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ .
So , following \cref{prop:opt_belief_KL,prop:opt_behavior_KL} , the optimal belief and behavior of Receiver are given by
\begin{equation*}
\eta(\mu)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\mathlarger{\mu} & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu<\tilde{\mu} \\ \\
\mathlarger{\frac{\mu\exp(\theta)}{\mu\exp(\theta)+(1-\mu)}} & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu\geq\tilde{\mu} \end{array}
\right.,
\end{equation*}
and
\begin{equation*}
a(\eta(\mu))=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu\geq\tilde{\mu} \\
0 & \mathrm{if} \quad \mu<\tilde{\mu}
\end{array}\right.,
\end{equation*}
for any $\mu\in\mathopen[0,1\mathclose]$ , where
\begin{equation*}
\tilde{\mu}=\frac{\exp(\theta\lambda)-1}{\exp(\theta)-1}.
\end{equation*}
