A voter $i$ with belief $\eta_i\in\Delta(\Omega)$ and partisan preferences $u_i$ votes for the proposal if and only if $\langle\eta_i,u_i\rangle=\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\eta_i(\omega)u_i^\omega$ is greater than $0$ such that the optimal voting strategy of any voter is
\begin{equation*}
a(\eta_i,u_i)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \mathrm{if} \quad \langle\eta_i,u_i\rangle\geq 0 \\
0 & \mathrm{if} \quad \langle\eta_i,u_i\rangle < 0
\end{array}\right.,
\end{equation*}
for any $\eta_i\in\Delta(\Omega)$ , $u_i\in\mathbb{R}^{|\Omega|}$ .

Next proposition exhibits the properties of Receiver 's optimal beliefs and well - being as a function of the Bayesian posterior induced by Sender .
\cref{sec:beliefs&behavior} .
\begin{proposition} [ Receiver 's optimal beliefs ]
\label{prop:opt_belief_as1}
Assume $C(\eta,\mu)$ satisfies \cref{as:1} for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Receiver 's optimal belief equals
\begin{equation}\
\eta(\mu)=\eta_a(\mu)
\end{equation}
whenever $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ is such that
\begin{equation*}
W_a(\mu)\geq W_{a'}(\mu),
\end{equation*}
for all $a'\neq a$ , where $\eta_a:\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\Delta(\Omega)$ is a continuously differentiable and nondecreasing function and $W_a:\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ is a continuous and strictly concave function .
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
The function $\eta_a:\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\Delta(\Omega)$ is defined implicitly by system of first order conditions
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:FOC}
u_{a}-\frac{1}{\theta}\nabla_{\eta}C(\eta,\mu)=0,
\end{equation}
for any $a\in A$ , where $u_{a}=[u(a,\omega)]_{\omega\in\Omega}$ so it is continuously differentiable from the Implicit Function Theorem and , as $W(\eta,\mu)$ is supermodular , it is increasing by Topkis theorem .
Continuity and strict concavity of $W_a:\Delta(\Omega)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ follow directly from the convex version of the Maximum Theorem .
\end{proof} Next result states , similarly as \cref{cor:stakes-dependent_beliefs_KL} , that Receiver 's only motive to distort beliefs is her preferences .
\begin{proposition} [ Stakes - dependent beliefs ]
\label{prop:stakes-dependent_beliefs_as1} Assume $C(\eta,\mu)$ satisfies \cref{as:1} for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ , then Receiver chooses to stay realist for action $a$ , i.e. , $\eta_a(\mu)=\mu$ for all $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ if , and only if , the payoff vector $u_a$ relative to action $a$ is invariant with respect to the state , i.e. , $u(a,\omega)=u\in\mathbb{R}$ for all $\omega\in\Omega$ .
\end{proposition}  \begin{proof}
First , remark that , when restricted to $a(\eta)=a$ , the well - being function is given by
\begin{equation*}
W(\eta,\mu)=\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\eta(\omega) u(a,\omega)-\frac{1}{\theta}C(\eta,\mu),
\end{equation*}
for every $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Fix action $a\in A$ and let $u(a,\omega)=u\in\mathbb{R}$ for all $\omega\in\Omega$ .
The well - being is given by \begin{align*} W ( \eta,\mu)&=\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}  \eta(\omega) u-\frac{1} {\theta } C (\eta , \mu ) \\ &= u - \frac{1} {\theta } C (\eta , \mu ) , \end{align*} for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
As the anticipatory utility does not depend on $\eta$ , maximizing $W(\cdot,\mu)$ is equivalent to minimize $C(\cdot,\mu)$ .
By \cref{as:1} , $C$ is minimized only at $\eta=\mu$ so $\eta_a(\mu)=\mu$ for all $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Conversely , assume $\eta_a(\mu)=\mu$ for all $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Remark first that we can always write
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\eta(\omega) u(a,\omega)= u(a,\bar{\omega})+\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\eta(\omega) \left[u(a,\omega)-u(a,\bar{\omega})\right],
\end{equation*}
for any $\bar{\omega}\in\Omega$ , any $a\in A$ and any $\eta\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
Hence , the well - being function writes
\begin{equation*}
W(\eta,\mu)= u(a,\bar{\omega})+\sum_{\omega\in\Omega}\eta(\omega)\left[u(a,\omega)-u(a,\bar{\omega})\right] -\frac{1}{\theta}C(\eta,\mu)
\end{equation*}
By definition of $\eta_a(\mu)$ the following system of first - order conditions must be true
\begin{equation*}
\delta^{\bar{\omega}}-\frac{1}{\theta}\nabla_{\eta}C(\mu,\mu)=0
\end{equation*}
where $\delta^{\bar{\omega}}=[u(a,\omega)-u(a,\bar{\omega})]_{\omega\in\Omega}$ .
However , by \cref{as:1} , it must be that $\nabla_{\eta}C(\mu,\mu)=0$ .
Therefore , $\delta^{\bar{\omega}}=0$ meaning that $u(a,\omega)=u(a,\bar{\omega})$ for any $\omega\in\Omega$ .
\end{proof}
We now prove that Receiver always distort beliefs more intensely in the direction of her preferred states of the world , similarly to \cref{cor:wishful_overoptimism_KL} .
We build on convex analysis techniques , already introduced by \citet*{Bracha2012} , to derive Receiver 's wishful overoptimism bias .
So our proof is somehow an adaptation of their results to our framework .
Before stating the result , first remark the system of first order conditions
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:FOC}
u_{a}-\frac{1}{\theta}\nabla_{\eta}C(\eta,\mu)=0,
\end{equation}
for any $a\in A$ also defines implicitly $\eta_a$ as a function of the payoff vector $u_a$ .
\begin{proposition} [ Wishful overoptimism ]
Assume $C(\eta,\mu)$ satisfies \cref{as:1} for any $\eta,\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
The map $\eta_a(\cdot,\mu):\mathbb{R}^{|\Omega|}\longrightarrow\Delta(\Omega)$ is monotone in the payoff vector $u_a$ , i.e. ,
\begin{equation*}
\langle\eta_a(u_a,\mu)-\eta_a(u_{a'},\mu),u_a-u_{a'}\rangle\geq 0
\end{equation*}
\end{proposition} for any $a,a'$ such that $a\neq a'$ and any $\mu\in\Delta(\Omega)$ .
\begin{proof}
Let us first assume that $u(a,\omega)\neq u(a,\omega')$ for some $\omega,\omega'\in\Omega$ .
By \cref{prop:stakes-dependent_beliefs_as1} , we thus know that $\eta_a\neq\mathrm{Id}_{\Delta(\Omega)}$ so Receiver distorts beliefs in some direction .

Since the voting mechanism $x:A^n\longrightarrow X$ is given by
\begin{equation*}
x(a_1,\dots,a_n)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
1 & \mathrm{if} \quad \sum_{i\in N}a_i\geq\frac{n+1}{2} \\
0 & \mathrm{if} \quad \sum_{i\in N}a_i<\frac{n+1}{2}
\end{array}
\right.,
\end{equation*}
we can express Sender 's utility as a function of the voting profile by defining $v(a_1,\dots,a_n)= v(x(a_1,\dots,a_n))$ .
Hence , Sender 's indirect utility is given by
\begin{equation*}
\hat{v}(\mu)= v(\hat{a}_1(\mu),\dots,\hat{a}_n(\mu))=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
