\subsubsection{Cost functions respecting \cref{as:1} } \label{secap:extensions_as1}
In this section , we check if the results we exposed in \cref{sec:beliefs&behavior} extend qualitatively to the case where the psychological cost function satisfies \cref{as:1} .
Assume henceforth that $A$ and $\Omega$ are finite sets .

To conclude , remember that Receiver 's equilibrium belief always corresponds , by assumption , to the belief preferred by Sender .
We just proved that $0<\eta_0(\tilde{\mu})<\lambda<\eta_1(\tilde{\mu})<1$ .
Hence , at belief $\tilde{\mu}$ Sender always prefers Receiver to hold belief $\eta_1(\tilde{\mu})$ since it induces Receiver to take action $a=1$ .
Accordingly , the optimal belief function of Receiver is exactly
\begin{equation*}
\eta(\mu)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
